CARMEN XV.

This ode combines with the lyric something of the spirit of the Epodes. It is impos· sible to say why Horace chose so often this same subject, but he always handles it very sharply. (See C. i. 253 iv. 13.) There are not wanting, of course, those who suppose he wrote under the influence of his own disappointments, and who find particular periods of his life suitabie for the composition of each. This too has accordingly had diffeoent dama assigned it. But 1 need not trouble the reader with such discussions.
